	journal = {Journal of Political Economy},
	author = {Gilligan, Thomas W.},
	year = {2004},
	pages = {1157--1180},
	annote = {Given adverse selection, durable goods that trade less frequently depreciate more quickly.
Leasing increases the average quality of goods available.
 
Asymmetric information present in the market for used aircraft and leasing ameliorates the problem




Hendel and Lizzeri (2002) also show that leasing contracts, by increasing the average quality of durable goods transacted in used markets, serve to mitigate the con- sequences of adverse selection.




I test these predictions using data from the market for used business aircraft in North America over the period 1980–99. I find that qualitative uncertainty and leasing patterns exert a statistically significant effect on the relationship between depreciation and trading volume and that these effects are consistent with the predictions of the theory. 




First, evidence of the insights contained in Akerlof’s (1970) seminal work is mixed and inconclusive in contemporary durable goods markets. Bond (1984) finds weak evidence of adverse selection among older trucks only. Genesove (1993) finds only modest evidence of adverse selection in dealer auction markets for used cars. Fabel and Lehmann (2000) and Emons and Sheldon (2003) find stronger support for the existence of adverse se- lection in used automobile markets. 












Porter and Sattler (1999) argue that their results are inconsistent with adverse selection in used automobile markets. 




Second, counteracting or extramarket institutions are often under- stood as solving or mitigating problems of qualitative uncertainty and the asymmetric distribution of information. The market for business aircraft exhibits many of these features. For example, it is common for transactions of used business aircraft to carry some form of limited guarantee or warranty of serviceability and performance. 




 












Hendel and Lizzeri (1999, 2002) constitute a framework for assessing the relevance of adverse selection and, when proxies for qualitative uncertainty are present, for testing broader classes of theory pertaining to patterns of trade in used durable goods. 
 




Consumers with a strong preference for quality wish to frequently re- place durables that deteriorate rapidly. With full information, prices reflect this rapid deterioration, and brands with high trading volumes depreciate more quickly. 
 




Hendel and Lizzeri (2002) show that the percentage of durable good units returned to the lessor exceeds the percentage of units traded in the used market under standard selling contracts and, thus, that leasing contracts increase the volume of trade in used durable goods markets. 




 








that the regulatory history of a particular aircraft is an important indicator of its potential qualitative uncertainty. 
 




However, it is generally appreciated and easy to document that the cumulative number of airworthiness directives and the cumulative number of ac- cidents associated with any aircraft brand are highly correlated 
 




Thus entering the cumulative number of airworthiness directives directly into estimations of the residual value function serves to control for any correlation that may exist between aircraft quality and reliability and test the proposition that any measure of aircraft reliability should be directly related to aircraft value.
 




Thus the estimations reported below use aircraft age as a weight in the computation of standard errors and permit correlated (i.e., clustered) errors for given models of aircraft. 




 








The parameter on the interaction between the volume of trade and the cu- mulative number of airworthiness directives variables is statistically less than zero (.0012 and p ! .05). 
 




All else equal, aircraft brands with higher levels of qualitative uncertainty (i.e., larger values of the cumulative number of airworthiness directives variables) exhibit a more negative relationship between trading volume and estimated depreciation. The parameter on the interaction between the volume of trade and the number of lease-operated aircraft variables is statistically greater than zero (.0006, p ! .05). All else equal, aircraft models with higher leasing frequencies exhibit a more direct relationship between trading volume and depreciation rates. Both of these findings are consistent with the notion that asymmetric information is a prominent feature of and that leasing mitigates adverse selection in the used aircraft market. 




 








 







},
	file = {lemons_leases.pdf:/Users/johannesmauritzen/Library/Mobile Documents/com~apple~CloudDocs/zotero/storage/J2223K8S/lemons_leases.pdf:application/pdf}
}

